# Prompt Engineering System

This system controls how AI behaves across LexMastery.

It is the behavior layer of intelligence.

---

# Product Vision

Prompts must:

- enforce consistent AI behavior
- define role-based instructions
- adapt to feature context
- control response structure
- prevent hallucination

---

# Prompt Types

1. System Prompts
2. Feature Prompts
3. Context Prompts
4. Mode Prompts
5. Retrieval Prompts (RAG-based)

---

# Architecture

PromptController (logical layer)

↓

PromptBuilder

↓

PromptTemplates

↓

AI Service

---

# Prompt Structure

Every prompt must include:

- role definition
- user context
- learning objective
- constraints
- output format rules

---

# Feature-Specific Prompts

Each module has custom prompts:

- AI Tutor Prompt
- Quiz Generation Prompt
- Flashcard Prompt
- Mock Exam Prompt
- Comparative Law Prompt

---

# Context Injection Rules

Prompts must dynamically include:

- user progress
- memory system data
- RAG results
- difficulty level
- jurisdiction context

---

# Safety Rules

Prompts must enforce:

- no hallucination
- citation requirement when needed
- structured responses
- legal accuracy constraints

---

# Mode Switching

Prompts change based on mode:

- Explanation Mode
- Exam Mode
- Practice Mode
- Revision Mode

---

# Offline Behaviour

- static prompt templates available offline
- dynamic context injection disabled offline

---

# API Contracts

POST /prompt/generate

GET /prompt/templates

POST /prompt/test

---

# Analytics Events

prompt_used

prompt_modified

prompt_error

---

# Performance

- prompt generation <50ms target
- cached templates preferred

---

# UX Rules

- prompts are invisible to users
- only affect AI behavior

---

# Testing Requirements

Unit Tests:

Prompt builder logic

Template rendering

Context injection

Integration Tests:

AI Tutor prompt flow

Quiz generation prompts

---

# Cursor Instructions

When generating AI features:

- always use structured prompts
- always include constraints
- always inject context dynamically
- never allow free-form unstructured prompts